 Relativism &ldquo;For &lsquo;to be&rsquo; and &lsquo;not to be&rsquo; coexist, without &lsquo;difficult&rsquo;, there cannot be &lsquo;easy&rsquo;; without &lsquo;long&rsquo; there cannot be &lsquo;short&rsquo;. The contrary completement each other&rdquo;.
&ldquo;Stooping, you will be preserved;
Wronged, you will be righted;
Hollow, you will be filled;
Worn out, you will be renewed;
Having little, you may gain;
Having much, you may be at a loss.&rdquo;12
 The softest thing in the world can penetrate the hardest.
&ldquo;Nothing in the world is softer and weaker than water, but nothing is better to win over the hard and the strong, for it cannot be replaced.&rdquo;
 &ldquo;Some hegemonic power tries in vain to conquer the world by force, because it does not know the reason why the weak may surpass the stong.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Once Confucious asked the Old Master for advice, who opened his toothless mouth without saying anything, but Confucious understood that he meant the soft outlasts the hard. Hearing this story Xin Qiji (1140-1207) wrote the following stanza:
 The hard may not be strong,
While the soft may last long.
See into my open mouth if you think me wrong:
The teeth are lost before the tongue.
  Laws Divine and Human, Lai Zi, China Ancient Literature, 500BC. ↩ Laws Divine and Human, Xu Yuanchong, Zhonghua Book Company, 2012. ↩

 He who does not show himself is seen everywhere; He who does not assert himself is well-known; He who does not boast wins success; He who is not proud can lead; As he contends for nothing, none in the world could contend with him. From Laws Divine and Human1, translation version by Yuanchong Xu2:
Divine law is not the common law  The divine law may be spoken of, but it is not the common law.
 By common law Lao Zi means those enforced by human beings. So we may see the difference between divine and human laws.
The divine law is objective truth which does not depend on human will for its existence, while human laws do. The former may be called natural philosophy, while the latter social philosophy. The former will not change when the latter does. That is the reason why Lao Zi says that the divine law is not the common law.
Non-interference The divine law will not interfere. Only when the law does not interfere can all things develop freely. So the law should always be inactive so as to let all things be active.
The activity of all things is the result of the law&rsquo;s inaction or non-interference. The law&rsquo;s inaction provides the condition for the activity of all things. When we say there is nothing the law cannot do, we mean that the activity of all things are the embodiment of the divine law. &ldquo;Therefore the sage does everything without interference, teaches everyone without persuasion, and lets everything begin uninitiated and grow unpossessed. Everything is done without being his deed, and succeeds without being his success.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Therefore the sage says, &lsquo;if I do nothing wrong, the people will go the right way&rsquo;&rdquo;
Thus we see &ldquo;to rule by inaction or non-interference&rdquo; is an important priciple of the Old Master&rsquo;s political philosophy.
Non-contention As a result of inaction, the Old Master advocates non-contention. In Chapter 8 he says, &ldquo;The highest good (virtue) is like water. Water benefits everything by giving without taking or contending. It likes the low place others dislike, so it follows closely the divine law.&rdquo;
&ldquo;He who does not shown himself is seen everywhere. He who does not assert himself is well-known. He who does not boast wins success. He who is not proud can lead. As he contends for nothing, none in the world could contend with him.&rdquo;
Desire control How can the principle of non-contention be carried out?
&ldquo;Be simple and plain, selfless and desireless&rdquo;: If you can control or subdue your desire, of course you will not contend for personal profit. That is the reason why the Old Master says in Chapter 1, &ldquo;So we should be free from desires in order to understand the internal mystery of the divine law, and we should have desires in order to observe the external manifestaions.&rdquo; Only when you understand the divine law inwardly and outwardly can you be selfless and desireless.
Contentment How can we control or subdue our desire?
The Old Master puts forward his principle of contentment in Chapter 13: : It needs observation to know others but reflection to know onself. Physically strong, one can conquer others; mentally strong, one can conquer oneself. Content, one is rich.&rdquo;
That is to say, if you know yourself through reflection, you will become mentally strong and conquer yourself. Content, you can control your desire.
In Capther 46, he further says, &ldquo;No crime is greater than insatiable desire, no woe is greater than covetise. If you know contentment comes from being content, you will always have enough.&rdquo; That is to say, if you are mentally content, then you will have enough material.
Non-interference, non-contention, desire-control and contentment are the four important principles of the Old Master&rsquo;s philosophy.
